2025-11-04 | Second Largest Element in an Array

Problem Statement
Given an array of positive integers arr[], return the second largest element from the array.
If the second largest element doesn’t exist, return -1.

Note:
The second largest element must be strictly smaller than the largest element — duplicates of the largest don’t count.

Approach / Explanation
	1.	Observation
•	We need two variables:
	•	max1 → to store the largest element.
	•	max2 → to store the second largest distinct element.
	2.	Steps
•	Initialize max1 with the first element and max2 with -1.
•	Traverse the array:
	•	If the current element is greater than max1, then max2 = max1 and update max1.
	•	Else if the current element is less than max1 but greater than max2, update max2.
•	Return max2.
	3.	Time and Space Complexity
•	Time Complexity: O(n) (single traversal).
•	Space Complexity: O(1) (constant extra space).

SOLUTION:
class Solution {
  public:
    int getSecondLargest(vector<int> &arr) {
        if (arr.size() < 2)
            return -1;

        int max1 = arr[0];
        int max2 = -1;

        for (int i = 1; i < arr.size(); i++) {
            if (arr[i] > max1) {
                max2 = max1;
                max1 = arr[i];
            } else if (arr[i] < max1 && arr[i] > max2) {
                max2 = arr[i];
            }
        }

        return max2;
    }
};
